en","1616–1687":"1616–1687","1547–Male":"1547–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1547":"1547","1687":"1687","abt 1590":"circa 1590","1590":"1590","1616":"1616","United States":"Verenigde Staten van Amerika","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"abt 1590–":"about 1590–Deceased","1590–Female":"1590–Deceased","1590–Male":"1590–Deceased","1616–1687":"1616–1687","1547–Male":"1547–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1547":"1547","1687":"1687","abt 1590":"about 1590","1590":"1590","1616":"1616","United States":"United States","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"Hurst","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form, first recorded in the 15th century, of the Old Saxon name <i>Horsa</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Hurst was born about 1590, in United States as the daughter of William Hurst and ?. She had at least 1 daughter with John Tilley. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"abt 1590–":"umbes 1590–Surnud","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","1590–Male":"1590–Surnud","1616–1687":"1616–1687","1547–Male":"1547–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1547":"1547","1687":"1687","abt 1590":"umbes 1590","1590":"1590","1616":"1616","United States":"Ameerika Ühendriigid","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1590–":"noin 1590–Kuollut","1590–Female":"1590–Kuollut","1590–Male":"1590–Kuollut","1616–1687":"1616–1687","1547–Male":"1547–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1547":"1547","1687":"1687","abt 1590":"noin 1590","1590":"1590","1616":"1616","United States":"Yhdysvallat","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1590–":"environ 1590–Décédée","1590–Female":"1590–Décédée","1590–Male":"1590–Décédé","1616–1687":"1616–1687","1547–Male":"1547–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1547":"1547","1687":"1687","abt 1590":"environ 1590","1590":"1590","1616":"1616","United States":"États-Unis","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Hurst est née environ 1590, à États-Unis, fille de William Hurst et ?. Elle a eu au moins 1 fil